## Phase 2 — Diagram generation

Only after Phase 1 is complete, produce the two diagrams.

### 2.1 Mermaid sequence diagram

Requirements:

- Use `sequenceDiagram` with `autonumber`
- Declare every lifeline with `participant` (use short aliases for arrow lines)
- Wrap each scenario in a `rect rgb(...)` block with the color coding below
- Use `Note over` for architectural insights and contract callouts — not just
  to repeat what an arrow says
- Use `activate` / `deactivate` to show nesting (component is “active” during
  a sub-call)
- Use `loop` blocks for repeated events (e.g., per-token streaming)
- Use `--x` for exception throws, `-->>` for async/return, `->>` for sync calls
- Reference real function names, file paths, and error codes from the
  codebase — do not invent them

Color palette for scenario bands:

|Scenario type    |RGB               |When to use                             |
|-----------------|------------------|----------------------------------------|
|Happy path       |rgb(211, 249, 216)|Clean successful execution              |
|Contained failure|rgb(255, 244, 230)|Recovered internally, run still succeeds|
|Escalated failure|rgb(255, 227, 227)|Fatal — user sees error                 |
|Network/transport|rgb(231, 245, 255)|Connection-level failure                |
|Cancellation     |rgb(243, 240, 255)|User-initiated abort                    |

Output the Mermaid file as a complete `.mmd` document with:

- Header comment listing scenarios and their tags
- Brief comment block per scenario explaining what makes it interesting

### 2.2 Excalidraw JSON sequence diagram

Requirements:

- Generate Excalidraw v2 JSON (importable into excalidraw.com)
- Lifelines as horizontal labeled boxes at top, vertical dashed lines descending
- Each scenario gets a colored band divider (full-width labeled rectangle)
- Messages as horizontal arrows between lifelines, labeled
- Self-calls as small loop indicators on a single lifeline
- Notes as colored boxes spanning relevant lifelines
- Activation bars as thin colored vertical rectangles overlaid on lifelines
- Color coding matches the Mermaid palette above
- Solid arrows for sync calls, dashed for returns/async/logging
- Include a legend at the bottom

Use the following palette (must be consistent with the architecture diagram
if one exists):

```
Frontend     bg=#e7f5ff stroke=#1971c2
Transport    bg=#fff4e6 stroke=#e8590c
Orchestration bg=#f3f0ff stroke=#6741d9
Agent layer  bg=#e6fcf5 stroke=#0ca678
Tool layer   bg=#fff9db stroke=#f08c00
Cross-cutting bg=#ffe0e6 stroke=#c2255c
Persistence  bg=#dee2e6 stroke=#495057
```

Output as a complete JSON object with `type: "excalidraw"`, `version: 2`,
`source`, `elements: [...]`, `appState`, `files: {}`. Validate that every
element has the required fields: `id`, `type`, `x`, `y`, `width`, `height`,
`angle`, `strokeColor`, `backgroundColor`, `fillStyle`, `strokeWidth`,
`strokeStyle`, `roughness`, `opacity`, `groupIds`, `frameId`, `roundness`,
`seed`, `version`, `versionNonce`, `isDeleted`, `boundElements`, `updated`,
`link`, `locked`. Text elements additionally need `text`, `fontSize`,
`fontFamily`, `textAlign`, `verticalAlign`, `containerId`, `originalText`,
`lineHeight`, `baseline`. Arrow/line elements need `points`,
`lastCommittedPoint`, `startBinding`, `endBinding`, `startArrowhead`,
`endArrowhead`.

Layout guidance:

- Lifelines spaced ~230px apart horizontally
- Each scenario should fit in 400–700 vertical pixels
- Total diagram height typically 2000–3000px
- Title and subtitle at top; legend at bottom

