## Constraints

- **Use real names from the codebase**: function names, error codes,
  exception types, log message text. Do not paraphrase or generalize. If the
  code says `loggingHelper.log(type="ERROR", errorCode="E1020")`, the diagram
  says `loggingHelper.log E1020`, not “logger logs an error.”
- **Reference file paths and line numbers** in the analysis report. Reviewers
  must be able to trace every diagram element back to source.
- **Don’t invent failure modes**. If the code doesn’t have a circuit breaker,
  don’t put one in the diagram. If retries aren’t bounded, say so — don’t
  invent a bound.
- **Surface inconsistencies**. If two parts of the codebase handle similar
  failures differently (e.g., one path emits RUN_ERROR but another silently
  closes), call this out in the annotations section. The diagrams should
  reflect what’s actually there, even when it’s inconsistent.
- **Keep scenarios focused**. Each scenario should illustrate ONE primary
  failure mode plus its surrounding context. Don’t try to show every possible
  branch in one scenario.
- **Activation bars must match call depth**. If component A calls B which
  calls C, A’s activation bar must visibly span B’s, which spans C’s. This is
  what makes nested call structures readable.
- **Notes earn their place**. Use notes for architectural insights, contract
  callouts, or non-obvious decisions (“★ Tool failure does NOT raise — keeps
  agent in control of conversation”). Don’t use notes to repeat what an arrow
  already says.
- **Color consistency**: a component should appear in the same color
  everywhere it shows up across both diagrams.

